\details{
An \code{Informer} performs an initial list of a resource, then watches for
subsequent changes and maintains a local cache keyed by
\code{namespace/name} (or just \code{name} for cluster-scoped resources). Event
handlers fire on add/update/delete.

This is the R equivalent of client-go's \code{SharedIndexInformer}. Informers
are the canonical way to build controllers: one watch feeds many handlers
and many \link{Lister} views, without each consumer re-listing the API server.

Lifecycle:
\itemize{
\item \verb{$run(stop_seconds = NULL)} — block, streaming events into the cache.
Returns when \code{stop_seconds} elapses, the stream callback returns FALSE,
or \verb{$stop()} is called. Safe to re-invoke; the informer resumes from
the last observed resourceVersion (or re-lists on 410 Gone).
\item \verb{$has_synced()} — \code{TRUE} once the initial list has been absorbed.
\item \verb{$lister()} — return a \link{Lister} view over the current cache snapshot.
}
}
\examples{
\dontrun{
client <- new_client_from_config()
inf <- Informer$new(
  client,
  resource_path = "/api/v1/namespaces/default/pods",
  object_from_list = V1Pod$from_list
)
inf$add_event_handler(
  on_add    = function(obj) message("add: ", obj$metadata$name),
  on_update = function(old, new) if (!identical(old$status, new$status))
                                   message("status change on ", new$metadata$name),
  on_delete = function(obj) message("gone: ", obj$metadata$name)
)
inf$run(stop_seconds = 30)
pods <- inf$lister()
pods$get("nginx")
pods$list()
}
